nt><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=35.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: ..the luddites are right..?</span><hr size=1> A society like that might evolve into a group of people who are willing to sacrifice so that future generations can thrive so the careful management might be towards the construction of a assets to get into space at some point it would be cost effective to go to space. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>spacefaring rodent</span><br>  Posts: 1149<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/15/03 1:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=35.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: ..the luddites are right..?</span><hr size=1> The biggest problem with the luddites is that they think we will be forever locked into our current technological state.  They think that fifty or a hundred years from now we'll still be burning fossil fuels in our vehicles, using the same dirty manufacturing processes, generating most of our electricity from coal, etc.  Human ingenuity is certainly capable of overcoming all of these environmental problems, not only will we likely have abundant fusion power stations that are completely emissions free and be completely void of long lived radioactive waste, but we will likely have mastered the use of hydrogen as fuel and technologies like nanofactories coupled with quantum computing would clean up a lot of industrial operations.  Within a hundred years we may have Star Trek style synthesizers that can create just about anything from a raw stock of chemical elements.  Such technology would go a very long way toward ending hunger and poverty as we know it, but of course the luddites try to scare the hell out of us by telling us that these types of technologies are too powerful for us and that we basically need to start exterminating ourselves according to their &quot;enlightened&quot; plans to survive or more aptly to let more &quot;legitimate&quot; lifeforms flourish in our absence.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :smash --><img src=http://pages.prodigy.net/rogerlori1/emoticons/smashf.gif ALT=":smash"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 150<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/15/03 2:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=35.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: ..the luddites are right..?</span><hr size=1> The unknown scares people.  Whenever humanity gets a new power, inevitably people caution its destructive power.  It was not until the last 100 years that we achieved the capabilities of wiping out our existence.  This possibility of the &quot;end of history&quot; is a very real one.  Everyday it becomes easier and easier to destroy ourselves and unless we move beyond this planet it is likely only a matter of time before it happens.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately this is the nature of the beast and there is no turning back without major social upheaval.  As our technology grows, so does our destructive capabilities.  With great power must come great wisdom else disaster is inevitable.  The only real solution (and it is only partial at best) to the problem is to instill wisdom i.e. the knowledge of applying knowledge for benefit of all mankind.  Those in power must understand their responsibility in using technology.<br>
<br>
This is why I feel the world needs to be educated and modernized.  The third world has all its knowledge vested in the elite.  These elite lead a relatively ignorant and fearful population who do not hold them accountable.  Everyday these few gain better and better capabilities and eventually one could be used to inflict significant harm on humanity for nothing else other than political or historical goals.  Removing said leaders from power (as seems current US policy) is but a temporary fix -- a short term (and ultimately futile) solution to a long term problem.  Ousting one dictator in Iraq may save us for now, but there is no shortage of enterpising and conquering souls out there.  In the decades to come I believe the problem can only intensify, unless we break this cycle of ignorance.<br>
<br>
Even if we do, we must still go off this planet to survive.  If we do not kill ourselves, the cosmos surely will.  This is why going back to &quot;simpler times&quot; will do nothing.  Even if it were realistic, we would be dooming ourselves.<br>
<br>
On a side note, people who are more educated tend to be more supportive of technological solutions to the world's problems.  For instance, those with a college background show significantly great support for nuclear energy than those with high school level education.  The number increases for those who went to college and studied sciences, especially the physical sciences.<br>
<br>
A couple fun fear blasts from the past:<br>
<br>
Opponents of electricity (esp. alternating current) would fabricate posters on how &quot;Current Kills&quot; and how deadly it would be to children and the accidents would be &quot;unacceptable&quot;.  <br>
<br>
People protested the machine gun citing that if we lined up the world's population and just fired away.  Within a month (the world was a less occupied then) every man, woman, and child would be dead.<br>
